export const MANIFEST_INSTRUCTIONS = "Manifest is living documentation for the software you are building. It tracks features -- the capabilities your system provides -- as living documents that evolve with your codebase.\n\n## Domain terms\n\n- **feature**: a system capability in the tree. Leaf features are workable; parents are feature sets.\n- **feature set**: a parent with children. Cannot be started directly -- work on its leaf children.\n- **spec**: the details field -- formatted per the project's spec template. Read with `get_feature`, write with `update_feature`, get format with `get_template`.\n- **proof**: recorded test output linked to a feature. Record with `prove_feature`.\n- **tree**: the full feature structure. Use `render_feature_tree`.\n- **version / milestone**: a semantic version grouping features. Use `list_versions`.\n\nFeature states: proposed, in_progress, implemented, blocked, archived.\n\n## Session Start\nAlways call orient with directory_path to discover the project and its current state.\n\n## Bootstrap Protocol (orient reports empty project)\n1. Gather input: read a PRD, ask the user to describe capabilities, or analyze the codebase yourself\n2. Analyze: decompose the input into a tree of capabilities (not tasks or phases). For each leaf, write a spec following the Spec Format below.\n3. Preview: call decompose with confirm=false to review the proposed tree\n4. Confirm: call decompose with confirm=true to create the features\n5. Root context: call update_feature on the root to set details (project overview, tech stack, conventions)\n6. Versions: call create_version for initial milestones, then set_feature_version to assign features\n\nWhen analyzing an existing codebase: read key files (README, package manifests, entry points, route definitions), examine git log for recent activity, and identify existing capabilities. Set state to \"implemented\" for features already built, and check off their acceptance criteria with [x].\n\nAfter creating features, discover and record existing tests:\n1. Identify the test runner from project config (package.json scripts, Makefile, Cargo.toml, pyproject.toml)\n2. Find test files by convention (*.test.ts, *_test.go, test_*.py, *_spec.rb, etc.)\n3. Run the test suite with verbose flags (vitest run --reporter=verbose, pytest -v, go test -v ./..., rspec --format documentation)\n4. Map test files and suites to the implemented features they cover using file paths, imports, and test descriptions\n5. Call prove_feature for each implemented feature with matching tests, passing structured test_suites, evidence file paths, and the current commit_sha\nSkip if no test files or runner are found. Record failing tests too -- they document existing coverage.\n\nCall `get_template` to fetch the project's spec template before writing leaf specs. If no custom template is configured, use the default format below.\n\n## Spec Format\n\nLeaf feature details (50-150 words) MUST follow this structure:\n1. User story opening: \"As a [user], I can [capability] so that [benefit].\"\n2. Brief context (1-2 sentences): key behavior, constraints, or edge cases.\n3. Acceptance criteria as checkbox items (3-5): concrete assertions verifiable in specs and tests.\n\nNever repeat the feature title in the details -- the title is displayed separately in the UI.\nWrite what agents cannot discover from code (business rules, edge cases, product intent). Do NOT include file paths, directory layouts, or implementation approach.\n\nExample:\n\nAs a user, I can mark a todo as complete so that I can track my progress.\n\nTapping the checkbox next to a todo toggles its completed state. Completed todos display with strikethrough styling.\n\n- [ ] Checkbox appears to the left of each todo item\n- [ ] Clicking the checkbox toggles the completed boolean\n- [ ] Completed todos render with line-through text decoration\n- [ ] Toggling is immediate -- no confirmation dialog\n\nParent features use details for shared architectural context, patterns, and constraints for children. Parent details flow to all children via breadcrumb -- put shared decisions there, not in every leaf.\n\n## Work Protocol\nget_next_feature -> start_feature -> assess_plan -> implement -> prove_feature -> update_feature (spec) -> complete_feature\n\n## Conventions\n- Features describe capabilities (\"Image upload\"), not tasks (\"Set up S3 bucket\")\n- Parent features hold shared context in details; leaf features are implementable units\n- All features should be assigned to a version\n- Proof (test evidence) is required before completing a feature\n\n## Output rules\n\nSome tools return pre-formatted text (`render_feature_tree`, `get_project_history`). Do NOT repeat, summarize, or reformat their output -- the tool result is already displayed to the user." as const;
